#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run --script
# /// script
# requires-python = ">=3.11"
# dependencies = [
#   "textual>=0.60",
#   "mitmproxy>=11",
#   "wcmatch>=8.4",
#   "pyfuse3>=3.2",
#   "trio>=0.22",
# ]
# ///
"""
slopbox — run an untrusted process in an unprivileged bwrap slopbox.

    slopbox                 start the UI (network approval + change review)
    slopbox CMD [ARGS...]   run CMD slopboxed

Network model: the slopbox has NO real network — only loopback. A tiny
forwarder inside the slopbox listens on 127.0.0.1:8080 (the proxy the program
is told to use) and hands each accepted connection's FD out to the UI over a
Unix socket (SCM_RIGHTS). The UI feeds that socket to an in-process mitmproxy,
which gates it against the rules / asks you, and performs the real upstream
fetch in the UI's own network context. No slirp, no host ports reachable from
the slopbox, no proxy listening anywhere the slopbox could abuse. If no UI is
running, the forwarder has nowhere to hand connections, so the slopbox simply
has no network — it never blocks waiting on an absent human.

Filesystem model: the UI owns ONE pyfuse3 overlay mount, served from a
dedicated trio thread and created the ordinary way (`pyfuse3.init` via the
setuid `fusermount3` helper — no root, no user namespace, no fd-passing, no
mount(2)/pivot_root anywhere). That single mount is *multiplexed*: its synthetic
root lists one subfolder per live slopbox, `<mnt>/<sid>`, each presenting a
copy-on-write overlay of lower=`/` plus that session's private upper (backing
dir holds only `live/<sid>/up`; overlay state lives in the per-box
`<sid>.sqlar`). A slopbox writing to
`<mnt>/<sid>/etc/hostname` reads through to the host file unless it wrote there.

Because the UI serves every filesystem op, it sits in the I/O path exactly like
it already does for network requests: the Changes view updates live as writes
happen, and a per-write policy hook (policy_check) is the obvious place where a
deny/prompt would attach. Provenance (pid/exe/argv of the writer) is captured
synchronously and recorded in the per-box `<sid>.sqlar`. Since the UI is now the
mount provider,
`slopbox CMD` REQUIRES a running UI and fails fast otherwise.

Isolation is UNCHANGED: the runner still does `bwrap --bind <mnt>/<sid> / …`
with the same flags (own PID/IPC/UTS/net namespaces, all caps dropped, runs as
you). The bind-as-root confines the box to its own subfolder; it cannot reach
`<mnt>/` or another session's `<sid>`. Same uid as the UI, so no allow_other.

Options (slopbox [FLAGS] -- CMD ...; the command MUST follow `--`):
  -n         enable networking via mitmproxy (default: off)
  -t         enable process tracing (default: off)
  -d         direct host access / no capture (default: off)
  -w HOST    pre-allow HOST for this session (repeatable)
  -C DIR     working directory inside the slopbox (default: cwd)

A session is named by the time it started and the runner's pid
(YYYYmmdd-HHMMSS_PID); that name is the live/ subfolder and the mount
subfolder, and the only thing stored besides the captured changes is the
command itself.
"""

